subSection.paragraph:
Momordica charantia

L. (
Cucurbitaceae
), also known as an edible bitter melon (English), goya (
Japan
), or kugua (Chinese area), originating in 
India
, is now widely cultivated in Asia, South America, and Africa. 

M. charantia

has been used as an herbal medicine for hundreds of years to treat cough, liver heating, stomachic complaints, anthelmintic, and diabetes-related diseases (
Cortez-Navarrete et al., 2018
; 
Jia et al., 2017
). Previous pharmacological investigations of 

M. charantia

have revealed various biological activities, such as antiviral (
Bourinbaiar and Lee-Huang, 1995
; 
Lee-Huang et al., 1995
; 
Jiratchariyakul et al., 2001
), antitumor (
Lee-Huang et al., 1995
; 
Jilka et al., 1983
; 
Akihisa et al., 2007
), antiulcer (
Guebuz et al., 2000
), antidiabetic (
Kar et al., 2003
; 
Kumar et al., 2009
; 
Shivanagoudra et al., 2019
), anti-obesity (
Fan et al., 2019
; 
Huang et al., 2008
), antibacterial (
Coutinho et al., 2010
), and anti-inflammatory (
Bourinbaiar and Lee-Huang, 1995
; 
Shivanagoudra et al., 2019
; 
Yang et al., 2018
) activity.

Some pharmacological reports have shown that the isolated components and aqueous extracts from 

M. charantia

exert hypoglycemic effects by elevating GLP-1 secretion (
Huang et al., 2013
; 
Bhat et al., 2018
). Glucagon-like peptide 1 (GLP-1) has been suggested to be an important antidiabetic incretin hormone that is secreted from intestinal L cells. GLP-1 possesses a glucose-dependent insulin stimulatory effect, boosts β- cell function, and suppresses hepatic glucose production and glucagon secretion (
Edwards, 2005
; 
Tuduri et al., 2016
). Since GLP-1 is rapidly degraded by dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DDP4) 
in vivo
, generating stable DPP4-resistant GLP-1 analogs or small molecule-based DPP4 inhibitors has become a major strategy for the treatment of diabetes (
Edwards, 2005
; 
Langley et al., 2007
). However, modulation of endogenous GLP-1 levels by using agents that stimulate intestinal GLP-1 secretion has also gradually gained more attention (
He and Chu, 2020
; 
Kato et al., 2015
). In the present study, the GLP-1 secretory effect of isolated cucurbitanes was evaluated in a murine intestinal secretin tumor cell line (STC-1). The anti-NO production and cytotoxic activities of these compounds are also reported herein.
